Short answer: use the **Responses API “background mode”** and either **poll** or **use webhooks**. In background mode, your initial POST returns immediately (status `queued`), so you’re no longer bound by client/proxy timeouts. You don’t need to set a timeout value on the long-running generation itself—only on your short polling requests or your webhook receiver (which are quick). citeturn5search6turn6search1

Below are minimal, production-oriented patterns (Python + Node) copied straight from the official behavior described in the docs.

---

# 1) Fire-and-poll (no explicit timeout needed for the generation)

### Python
```python
from openai import OpenAI
import time

client = OpenAI()

# Kick off long-running reasoning task in background
resp = client.responses.create(
    model="o3",                 # or your reasoning model
    input="Do the multi-step analysis ...",
    background=True             # <-- key: background mode
)
rid = resp.id

# Poll until complete
while True:
    r = client.responses.retrieve(rid)
    if r.status in ("completed", "failed", "cancelled", "incomplete", "expired"):
        break
    time.sleep(2)  # short sleep between quick status checks

if r.status == "completed":
    # Extract output tokens
    print(r.output_text)
else:
    raise RuntimeError(f"Background task ended with status={r.status}")
```

### Node (TypeScript/JS)
```ts
import OpenAI from "openai";

const client = new OpenAI();

const start = await client.responses.create({
  model: "o3",
  input: "Do the multi-step analysis ...",
  background: true,            // <-- key: background mode
});

const id = start.id;

while (true) {
  const r = await client.responses.retrieve(id);
  if (["completed", "failed", "cancelled", "incomplete", "expired"].includes(r.status)) {
    if (r.status !== "completed") throw new Error(`status=${r.status}`);
    console.log(r.output_text);
    break;
  }
  await new Promise(res => setTimeout(res, 2000));
}
```

- The docs explicitly say to **poll while status is `queued` or `in_progress`** and read the result when it becomes `completed`. Status values include `queued | in_progress | failed | completed | canceled` (and some surfaces also document `incomplete/expired`). citeturn6search1turn6search0turn6search6  
- This pattern **avoids setting any long request timeout** on the generation; your only network calls are fast `GET /responses/{id}` polls. citeturn5search6

---

# 2) Fire-and-webhook (best when you don’t want to poll)

Configure a webhook and let OpenAI call you back when the background job finishes (event: **`response.completed`**; also handle `response.failed`). citeturn0search3turn5search5

### Kickoff (Python/Node are analogous)
```python
resp = client.responses.create(
    model="o3",
    input="Do the multi-step analysis ...",
    background=True,
    # If your project/webhook is configured in the dashboard, you don't need to pass URL here.
    # Some integrations allow passing a webhook override in the request; prefer project config per docs.
)
```

### Minimal webhook handler (Express)
```ts
import express from "express";
const app = express();
app.use(express.json()); // raw body if you verify signatures

app.post("/openai/webhooks", (req, res) => {
  const event = req.body; // verify signature per docs before trusting!
  // event.type is typically "response.completed" or "response.failed"
  if (event.type === "response.completed") {
    const response = event.data; // contains id, status=completed, output
    // persist response.output_text (or items[]) to your DB / queue downstream processing
  }
  res.sendStatus(200);
});

app.listen(3000);
```

- OpenAI’s **Webhooks guide** documents subscribing to background response events such as **`response.completed`**. This eliminates polling entirely and removes any need to set a timeout value for long generations. citeturn0search3turn5search5

---

# 3) Do I really have to set any timeout number?

- **For the long reasoning run**: **No**—that’s the point of background mode. Your long-lived work happens server-side; your client just receives an immediate `queued` response and later a quick poll result or webhook POST. citeturn5search6  
- **For synchronous calls** (not using background): the SDKs/clients have defaults (commonly ~10 minutes). Official guidance for long tasks is to **use background mode** (or streaming) rather than trying to disable timeouts. citeturn5search6turn0search2  
- **For polling**: keep the HTTP client’s timeout modest (these are short GETs). Even if you never tune it, you’re not waiting minutes on a single request—your loop just retries. (If you *do* hit a timeout, the **Error Codes** page says: retry with backoff.) citeturn1search18

---

# 4) When to prefer streaming instead

If you actually want the text as it’s produced (interactive UX) and to reduce perceived timeouts for long outputs, use **streaming** (SSE). It’s a separate technique from background mode; use it when you need progressive tokens in one live connection. citeturn0search2turn0search6

